After the try-catch block, guard against an empty embedding response before proceeding to the vector store:

if (!queryEmbedding) {
  console.warn('[noteQA] generateEmbeddings returned empty array; falling back to text search')
  return retrieveRelevantNotesByText(cleanQuery)
}

Alternatively, validate inside the try block: if (!embeddings[0]) throw new Error('Empty embeddings response'). This converts the undefined path into a caught error and routes it through the existing fallback.

Use a Unicode-aware pattern that includes accented letters, CJK, and other scripts:

function tokenize(value: string): string[] {
  return value.toLowerCase().match(/[\p{L}\p{N}]+/gu) ?? []
}

If ASCII-only is a deliberate scope decision (e.g., app only supports English), log a warning when queryTerms is empty so the silent degradation is visible: console.warn('[noteQA] Text fallback skipped: no tokenizable terms in query'). Also document the limitation in the JSDoc.

Clamp the final score to maintain consistent scale:

const similarity = Math.min(1, matchedTerms.length / queryTerms.length + phraseBoost)

Alternatively, document on RetrievedNote.similarity that text-fallback results may exceed 1.0 so callers are aware.
